Date: Sun, 24 Sep 2000 17:18:46 +0800
From: Dr Muruga Vadivale <cyberdoc@maxis.net.my>
Source: Reuters, Sun, 24 Sep 2000 17:27:56 +0800 [edited
<http://news.excite.com/news/r/000923/08/science-saudi-disease-dc>

Fever Kills 200 in Saudi Arabia and Yemen
--------------------------------------------------
DUBAI, United Arab Emirates: The death toll from Rift Valley Fever has
climbed to about 200 in Saudi Arabia and Yemen, medical sources and
newspapers said on Sat 23 Sep 2000. Authorities in Saudi Arabia said fresh
rainfall was making it difficult for emergency teams to fight the disease,
which is transmitted from livestock to humans by mosquitoes or through
contact with infected animals. Saudi sources told Reuters that "up to 100
people" had died in the kingdom from the viral disease which broke out
nearly 2 weeks ago. In neighboring Yemen, the death toll from the disease
had risen to around 100, a local newspaper said. Government figures released
in both countries are considerably lower. The Saudi health ministry has
reported 17 deaths and said that around 50 people were being treated in
hospitals. Yemen's health ministry has said that 17 people died in the
country.
Saudi Arabia shut down schools in Jizan province and banned the import of
sheep, goats and camels from Yemen and several African countries. The Saudi
sources, who declined to be named, said that the disease may have already
spread to areas outside Jizan, on the border with Yemen. They said that some
infected livestock may have found its way outside the province before health
measures were taken. Saudi Arabia has taken other precautions, including
requiring people traveling from Jizan to undergo medical tests, Saudi media
reported. The 2 neighbors have been cooperating in spraying
mosquito-infested areas along their common border with pesticides to control
the disease. Yemen had also called for international help to combat the
disease, which officials say had wiped out nearly half of the livestock in
the area of Wadi Moor in Hudeidah province.
Neighboring Gulf Arab states, Qatar and the United Arab Emirates, have said
they had not been affected by the disease but were taking preventive
measures, including a ban on import of livestock from several
countries.(Report updated to 23 Sep 2000, 8:11 AM ET)
--
