Date: Mon, 25 Sep 2000 10:55:44 GMT
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: Times of India, 25 Sep 2000 [edited

Rift Valley fever death toll now 24 in Saudi Arabia
---------------------------------------------------
RIYADH: Saudi Arabia's Health Ministry has said that 113 cases of Rift
Valley fever, 24 of them fatal, had been reported so far in the country,
since the disease first struck there on 11 Sep 2000. The Ministry in a
statement relayed by the official Saudi news agency, SPA, on Sat 23 Sep 2000
said that of the total infected, 96 were male.
The largest number of people infected, 98, live in the Jizan region, and all
the other cases were reported in areas on the border with Yemen. Ninety-two
people have died in Yemen of the disease, an agriculture ministry official
in Sana'a said on Fri 22 Sep 2000, but the Yemeni health minister Abdullah
Abdelwali said only 17 have died from the disease.
The Saudi authorities have stepped up the state of alert in the Kingdom to
stop the spread of the disease. It is the first time that the disease, which
affects domestic animals and can be transmitted to humans by mosquitoes,has
been known to strike outside Africa. The symptoms include haemorrhagic
fever, encephalitis and eye problems, although human deaths from the disease
are rare, according to experts.
The Saudi Agriculture Ministry announced on 18 Sep 2000 that it had
suspended livestock imports from Djibouti, Ethiopia, Eritrea, Somalia, Sudan
and Yemen, all of which are on the Red Sea. Yemen has also decided to ban
imports of livestock from Africa, the official Yemeni news agency Saba said
on Sat 23 Sep 2000.
