[3
Date: Mon, 25 Sep 2000 10:12:54 +0300
From: Shamsudeen Fagbo <oloungbo@zajil.net>
Source: Arab News, Mon 25 Sep 2000 [edited

Two Rift Valley fever cases detected in Riyadh
-----------------------------------------------
RIYADH: King Fahd, Custodian of the Two Holy Mosques, has ordered the
destruction of all livestock carrying or suspected of carrying the deadly
Rift Valley Fever (RVF) virus with immediate effect as the number of fatal
cases rose to 27 yesterday, the official Saudi Press Agency reported. He
also ordered quick payment of compensation to the livestock's owners.
In a press statement yesterday, the Health Ministry said 3 more people died,
2 of them in Jizan, during the past 24 hours bringing the total to 27. The
ministry also confirmed 14 new RVF cases including 2 in Riyadh, one each in
Jeddah and Najran, 3 in Asir and 7 in Jizan, bringing the total number of
people infected by the disease to = 129. The viral disease was first
reported on 11 Sep 2000 in the southern border city of Jizan.
The Governor of Jeddah, Prince Mishaal ibn Majed, confirmed that there was a
suspected RVF case in the city. He said the Governorate had taken
precautionary steps to prevent the spread of the disease. The Health
Ministry said 3 patients had recovered from the disease and had left the
Jizan hospital. It refuted press reports concerning 2 RVF cases admitted to
the King Fahd National Guard Hospital in Riyadh and the King Abdul Aziz
Hospital in Jeddah, saying that the patients were suffering from malaria and
liver-related illness respectively. The ministry said all RVF cases were
generally linked with Jizan and neighboring areas.
King Fahd's order to destroy infected livestock comes because the
potentially fatal virus is transmitted to humans through animals. According
to he Agriculture and Water Minister, Abdullah Muammar, RVF virus has killed
10 768 sheep, cows and camels in Jizan. As many as 16 212 sheep have aborted
and 153 000 animals have been treated against the disease. Speaking to
reporters after inspecting the areas worst hit by RVF in Jizan, Muammar said
the situation in Aridha, Uhd Al-Mesaraha and Wadi Jazan had returned to
normal after the government had taken measures to contain the disease.
Twenty-one additional special planes have been sent to Jizan to spray
insecticides on all affected areas in the region. He downplayed the panic
created by the spread of RVF in Jizan and other parts of the country and
said the disease had been found only in limited areas, making the efforts to
contain the killer virus easy.
The Health Minister, Dr. Osama Shubokshi, told a press conference in Jizan
on Sat 23 Sep 2000 that most of the patients affected by RVF were over 55.
and they had contracted the disease because of their inability to resist the
virus. He admitted, however, that it was not possible to say that the
disease was under total control. "The government is trying to control it by
all means. Our efforts in this respect will become fruitful within the next
few days," the minister told the conference. Shubokshi commended Saudi
doctors for their detection [confirmation of the disease 24 hours before
the results of tests had come back from the United States.
--
Shamsudeen Fagbo
<oloungbo@zajil.net>
