[4
Date: Mon, 25 Sep 2000 11:47:47 +0300
From: Shamsudeen Fagbo <oloungbo@zajil.net>
Source: Arab News, Sun 24 Sep 2000 [edited

Sheep smuggled from Yemen responsible for Jizan outbreak
--------------------------------------------------------
JIZAN/JEDDAH : Saudi authorities yesterday allayed fears about the spread of
Rift Valley Fever (RVF) by announcing the various measures taken by the
government to contain the disease which has killed 24 people and affected
113 others in Jizan. Potential cases of RVF have also been reported in
Jeddah. Two possible cases were admitted to the = emergency room of the
Al-Thaghr General Hospital last evening.
Agriculture and Water Minister, Dr. Abdullah Muammar, told a press
conference in Jizan yesterday that sheep smuggled from Yemen were
responsible for the spread [introduction of the virus into Jizan where
10 768 sheep, cows and camels have died over the past weeks. As many as
16 212 sheep have aborted and 153 000 animals were treated against RVF
infection he said. The press conference presided over by the Jizan Governor,
Prince Mishaal Al-Sudairy, was also addressed by the Minister of Health, Dr.
Osama Shubokshi, and the Minister of Municipal and Rural Affairs, Dr.
Muhammed Al-Jarallah. Senior government officials from the 3 ministries
were also present. They disclosed that no infection had been detected among
the sheep imported from African countries. However, the import ban on that
region would remain in place as a precautionary measure.
Earlier, Shubokshi and Jarallah, along with the accompanying delegation
visited the King Fahd Hospital in the city to inquire about the condition of
patients. Journalists from Riyadh were taken aboard a chartered Saudia
flight to Jizan for a briefing on the latest situation in the coastal city,
southwest of Riyadh, and government measures to combat the disease
transmitted to humans through infected sheep and camels. Providing an update
on the situation, Shobokshi said that RVF, first identified in Kenya's Rift
Valley in 1930, is also indigenous to southern and eastern Africa. "The
infected animals abort their fetus, and farmers who try to help them may
also fall victim to the virus." He said mosquitoes also acted as vectors of
the disease,which could thrive in the hot and humid climate of Jizan. The
situation was worsened by the recent rains which provided breeding grounds
for the mosquitoes. The minister, himself a medical doctor, said the
infection could be cured in 99 percent of cases, adding that complications
such as renal failure and hepatitis were reported in one percent of cases.
He disclosed that during the last 24 hours 10 additional RVF cases had been
reported. Several patients, discharged from various hospitals, were being
constantly monitored, even though they were in good health. To allay
concerns among the population, he pointed out that fears such as eating out
in restaurants were misplaced. Meat was safe so long as it had been prepared
hygienically.
Referring to the measures taken by the Agriculture Ministry. Muammar said
that the entry of all imported sheep through Jizan and other ports in the
Kingdom had been banned. The ban also applies to the local movement of these
animals in and out of this city as well as the rest of the country. The
Kingdom imports 1.5 million sheep annually. In this context. Muammar
confirmed that his ministry had received a letter from Saudi pharmacist
Ahmad Ali Hikami alerting them to the smuggling of infected sheep into the
Kingdom. However. the minister said no cases of viral infection were found
among the sheep imported from African countries. This had been proved later
as all the affected animals were brought in illegally from Yemen at cheap
rates.
Among the other measures outlined by the agriculture minister were the
aerial spraying of insecticides, for which 26 planes had been put into
service. This was in addition to 200-250 groups that had been mobilized for
mechanical spraying of insecticides. They were also touring villages and
farms to eradicate dead bodies of animals. "Experts from FAO and southern
Africa are coming here and they will be touring all the affected areas with
me tomorrow. Other measures will be announced on the completion of their
report," Muammar said.
Dr. Abdul Raheem Aqeel. director of health in Jizan, told Arab News that
they had launched a large-scale health awareness campaign through schools,
mosques and other community centers. Meanwhile schools reopened in Jizan
yesterday but attendance was thin. At King Khaled International Airport in
Riyadh passengers coming from Jizan must now have a blood test before
leaving the airport. Ghazi Mir. from the duty manager's office at Jeddah's
King Abdul Aziz Airport, said there were as yet no regulations or procedures
for people flying in from Jizan. "We are different from Riyadh as we still
don't have the disease," claimed Mir.
Six more possible RVF cases were also admitted to Qunfuda General Hospital,
near Jizan, yesterday. All 6 were Yemenis.
--
